Evaluate the limit

L = \lim_{x 	o 0}  rac{\sin(x) \cdot \arcsin(x) - x^2}{x^3 \ln(1+x) - x^4}

using a method that does NOT rely on L'Hôpital's Rule. Explain why repeated application of L'Hôpital's Rule would lead to a circular or non-terminating computation for this particular limit. Provide the exact rational value of L.

For each of the following four series, determine whether it converges absolutely (A), converges conditionally (C), or diverges (D).

**Series I:**  \displaystyle\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}  rac{\sin(n)}{n \ln n}

**Series II:** \displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}  rac{(-1)^n}{\sqrt[n]{n} - 1}

**Series III:** \displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}  rac{\ln(n!)}{n^2 \ln^2(n+1)}

**Series IV:** \displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}  rac{(-1)^{\lfloor\sqrt{n}floor}}{\sqrt{n}}

Select the ONE correct classification tuple (I, II, III, IV) from the options below:

(A) (C, D, A, C)
(B) (C, C, A, D)
(C) (A, D, C, C)
(D) (C, D, A, A)
